    body: [
      'Placeholder — describe your flagship web project here. What problem does it solve, who is it for, and what did you build? Focus on decisions that are interesting to other developers: the architectural choices, the constraints, the tradeoffs.',
      'What was the hardest technical problem? What would you do differently? What does this project say about how you approach engineering? Two or three paragraphs is the right length — enough to show depth, short enough to hold attention.',
      'Add a live URL or GitHub link if possible. Results matter here — not just what you built but what it did. Metrics, user numbers, performance improvements, or qualitative outcomes from real users.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Problem', 'The Hard Part', 'The Outcome'],
  },
  {
    id:       'project-2',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    '[Project Name]',
    meta:     '[Stack] · [Year]',
    body: [
      'Placeholder — a second development project. This one should show a different dimension of your engineering: a different domain, scale, or technical challenge. If your first project was frontend-heavy, this could be an API or a data-driven system.',
      'What made this one interesting to build? What were the constraints — time, budget, team size, performance requirements? Constraints are often where the most interesting engineering decisions happen.',
      'What is the outcome? Is it live? How many users? What is the load it handles? Concrete numbers are more compelling than adjectives. Replace the placeholders with your actual project details before publishing.',
    ],
    topics: ['A Different Angle', 'The Constraints', 'The Numbers'],
  },
  {
    id:       'project-3',
    category: 'PROJECT',
